# Web Quality Audit Workflow

When auditing web quality, use the skills in `.agents/skills/` systematically.

## Audit Order (by impact)

1. **Performance** — `.agents/skills/performance/SKILL.md`
   - Check performance budgets (JS < 300KB, CSS < 100KB, total < 1.5MB)
   - Verify LCP image has `fetchpriority="high"` and is preloaded
   - Check for render-blocking resources in `<head>`
   - Verify lazy loading on below-fold images

2. **Core Web Vitals** — `.agents/skills/core-web-vitals/SKILL.md`
   - LCP < 2.5s, INP < 200ms, CLS < 0.1
   - All images have width/height or aspect-ratio
   - No layout-triggering animations (use transform/opacity)
   - Event handlers complete < 100ms

3. **Accessibility** — `.agents/skills/accessibility/SKILL.md`
   - Color contrast ratios (4.5:1 normal text, 3:1 large text)
   - All images have alt text
   - All form inputs have labels
   - Keyboard navigation works (no traps)
   - Focus indicators visible
   - Target size ≥ 24×24px

4. **SEO** — `.agents/skills/seo/SKILL.md`
   - Title tags present and unique (50-60 chars)
   - Meta descriptions present (150-160 chars)
   - Single `<h1>` per page with proper hierarchy
   - Canonical URLs set
   - Structured data (JSON-LD) where applicable

5. **Best Practices** — `.agents/skills/best-practices/SKILL.md`
   - HTTPS everywhere, no mixed content
   - No deprecated APIs (document.write, sync XHR)
   - Security headers configured
   - No exposed source maps in production
   - Valid HTML, semantic elements

## Browser MCP Integration

When auditing a live page, combine skills with the `cursor-ide-browser` MCP:

- `browser_snapshot` for ARIA tree analysis (accessibility)
- `browser_console_messages` for errors (best practices)
- `browser_network_requests` for resource loading (performance)
- `browser_profile_start/stop` for CPU profiling (Core Web Vitals)
- `browser_take_screenshot` for visual review (CLS, contrast)

## Output Format

Structure findings by severity:
- **Critical** — fix immediately (security, keyboard traps, missing alt text)
- **High** — fix before launch (CWV failures, contrast issues)
- **Medium** — fix within sprint (SEO, performance opportunities)
- **Low** — fix when convenient (minor optimizations)
